*************************** T H E O R Y ************************* 7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
Talys is a computer code system for the prediction and analysis   7525 1451
of nuclear reactions. Talys simulates reactions that involve      7525 1451
neutrons, gamma-rays, protons, deuterons, tritons, helions and    7525 1451
alpha-particles, in the 1 keV - 20 MeV energy range and for       7525 1451
target nuclides of mass 12 and heavier. This is achieved by       7525 1451
implementing a suite of nuclear reaction models into a single     7525 1451
code system. It enables to evaluate nuclear reactions from        7525 1451
the unresolved resonance region up to intermediate energies. This 7525 1451
evaluation is based on a theoretical analysis that utilizes the   7525 1451
optical model, compound nucleus statistical theory, direct        7525 1451
reactions and pre-equilibrium processes, in combination with      7525 1451
databases and models for nuclear structure. The following output  7525 1451
of Talys is stored in this data file:                             7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
- Total, elastic and non-elastic cross sections                   7525 1451
- Elastic scattering angular distributions                        7525 1451
- Inelastic cross sections to discrete states                     7525 1451
- Inelastic scattering angular distributions to discrete states   7525 1451
- Exclusive channel cross sections, e.g. (n,g), (n,2n), (n,np),.. 7525 1451
- Exclusive channel energy spectra                                7525 1451
- Exclusive channel double-differential spectra                   7525 1451
- Exclusive gamma production for discrete states and continuum    7525 1451
- Isomeric and ground state cross sections                        7525 1451
- Residual production cross sections                              7525 1451
- Total particle cross sections, e.g. (n,xn), (n,xp),..           7525 1451
- Total particle energy spectra                                   7525 1451
- Total particle double-differential spectra                      7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
Here follows a short description of the used nuclear models:      7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
##### OPTICAL MODEL                                               7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
All optical model calculations are performed by ECIS-06 [ray94],  7525 1451
in Talys used as a subroutine. The default optical model          7525 1451
potentials (OMP) used are the local and global parameterizations  7525 1451
of Koning and Delaroche [kon03]. These are phenomenological OMPs  7525 1451
for neutrons and protons which in principle are valid over the    7525 1451
1 keV - 20 MeV energy range, though the low energy boundary of    7525 1451
validity may differ from nucleus to nucleus. For neutrons and     7525 1451
protons, the used parameterization is given in Eq. (7) of         7525 1451
[kon03]. To calculate the transmission coefficients and reaction  7525 1451
cross sections for deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha          7525 1451
particles, we use OMPs that are directly derived from our nucleon 7525 1451
potentials using Watanabe's folding approach.                     7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
##### DIRECT REACTIONS                                            7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
The built-in ECIS-06 is used for DWBA or coupled-channels         7525 1451
calculations for rotational or vibrational (or a combination of   7525 1451
these) nuclides, depending on the information present in the      7525 1451
nuclear structure database of Talys.                              7525 1451
In addition, a macroscopic, phenomenological model to describe    7525 1451
giant resonances in the inelastic channel is used. For each       7525 1451
multipolarity an energy weighted sum rule applies and a DWBA      7525 1451
calculation with ECIS-06 is performed for each giant resonance    7525 1451
state. The cross section is then spread over the continuum with a 7525 1451
Gaussian distribution.                                            7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
##### COMPOUND NUCLEUS                                            7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
For binary compound nucleus reactions we use the model of         7525 1451
Moldauer, i.e. the Hauser-Feshbach model corrected for width      7525 1451
fluctuations. The transmission coefficients have been generated   7525 1451
with the aforementioned OMPs and the full j,l-dependence of the   7525 1451
transmission coefficients in the Hauser-Feshbach model is used.   7525 1451
For each nucleus that can be reached through a binary reaction,   7525 1451
several discrete levels and a continuum described by level        7525 1451
densities are included simultaneously as competing channels.      7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
The compound nucleus angular distributions are calculated with    7525 1451
the Blatt-Biedenharn formalism, leading to compound nucleus       7525 1451
Legendre coefficients that are added to their direct              7525 1451
counterparts. For multiple compound emission, i.e. emitted        7525 1451
particles after the binary emission, we use the Hauser-Feshbach   7525 1451
model. Again, for each residual nucleus several discrete states   7525 1451
are included as well as a continuum described by level densities. 7525 1451
Multiple compound emission is continued until all reaction        7525 1451
channels are closed and the population distribution of all        7525 1451
residual nuclides is depleted, through gamma decay, until they    7525 1451
end up in the ground state or in an isomer.                       7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
For the level density, we take the Constant Temperature Model     7525 1451
with level density parameters as given in [kon08]. This employs   7525 1451
the temperature law at low energies and a Fermi gas expression at 7525 1451
high energies, and takes into account the damping of shell        7525 1451
effects at high excitation energy. We have obtained the level     7525 1451
density parameters from a simultaneous fit to all experimental    7525 1451
discrete levels and D0 values from the RIPL library [rip05].      7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
Gamma-ray transmission coefficients are generated with the        7525 1451
Kopecky-Uhl generalized Lorentzian for strength functions, with   7525 1451
giant dipole resonance parameters taken from the RIPL library     7525 1451
[rip05], and normalized with experimental radiative widths.       7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
##### PRE-EQUILIBRIUM REACTIONS                                   7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
For pre-equilibrium reactions, which become important for         7525 1451
incident energies above about 10 MeV, we use the two-component    7525 1451
exciton model [kon04], in which the neutron or proton types of    7525 1451
particles and holes are followed throughout the reaction. For     7525 1451
energies above 20 MeV, multiple pre-equilibrium emission up to    7525 1451
any order of particle emission was included in the calculations.  7525 1451
A parameterization for the squared matrix element is used that is 7525 1451
valid for the whole energy range of this evaluation.              7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
For deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha-particles, an extra     7525 1451
contribution was added from the pick/up and knock-out reaction    7525 1451
model by Kalbach [kal01].                                         7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
For photons, the model of Akkermans and Gruppelaar [akk85] was    7525 1451
applied, to simulate the direct and semi-direct capture           7525 1451
processes.                                                        7525 1451
                                                                  7525 1451
The angular distribution systematics by Kalbach [kal88] were used 7525 1451
to describe the angular distributions for all continuum           7525 1451
particles. An isotopic distribution for photons was adopted.      7525 1451
